_From @skybrian on September 20, 2017 19:46_

To reproduce, you need to type two switch statements:

```
func foo(x string) {
    switch x {
    default: 
    }
}

func bar(x string) {
    switch x {
    default:
    }
}
```

While typing "default" in the second switch statement, wait for the autocomplete to come up, showing a dropdown with "default" as one of the choices. (But don't trigger it.) Then, type the colon. (It will auto-indent, but the autocomplete pulldown is still up.) Then, type return.

The autocomplete will trigger, messing up the results:

```
switch x {
ddefault
}
```

It seems like this would be fixed if the autocomplete pulldown disappeared after typing the colon? At that point it's no longer useful.

_Copied from original issue: Microsoft/vscode-go#1234_

I have this JSON file:

```json
{
  "dependencies": {
    "something": "^1.0.5"
  },
  "foo|": 1
}
```

And this JS file:

```js
const obj = {
  "dependencies": {
    "something": "^1.0.5"
  },
  "foo|": 1
}
```

The `|` above indicates cursor position.

As you can see, the cursor is in the same location relative to the JavaScript object. Now if I invoke `document.getWordRangeAtPosition(selection.end);`...

On the JSON file I get the following Range:

```js
[
  { "line": 4, "character": 2 },
  { "line": 4, "character": 7 }
]
```

...but on the JS file, I get the following Range:

```js
[
  { "line": 4, "character": 3 },
  { "line": 4, "character": 6 }
]
```

Why are the ranges different on a JSON and JS file?
